The article discusses the significance of the National Cancer Act of 1971 and its impact on cancer research and treatment over the past 50 years. The act has led to the advancement of cancer screening, detection, and treatment options, as well as the establishment of research programs and networks. As a result, the overall cancer death rate in the United States has steadily declined, and there is hope for further progress in the fight against cancer. President Joe Biden emphasizes the importance of continued investment in cancer research and the need for equitable access to quality healthcare for all individuals affected by cancer. He also announces his plans to launch the Advanced Research Projects Agency for Health (ARPA-H) to accelerate breakthroughs in preventing, detecting, and treating cancer and other deadly diseases. The article concludes with a proclamation by President Biden, designating December 23, 2021, as the 50th Anniversary of the National Cancer Act of 1971 and calling for increased efforts in cancer research and care.